		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">http://www.fuckinggoogleit.com/<br /><br />hint: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.google.com/search?q=opening+famicom+cartridge">http://www.google.com/search?q=opening+ ... +cartridge</a><!-- m --></div>
<br />
<br />Thank you for being such a kind lovely individual. I did that exact search on google before posting here. There was like 1 answer to my question, and this was it:
<br />
<br />Cracking open a traditional Famicom cartridge without breaking any plastic tabs is not easy (some don’t use any screws). I’m not even going to try to describe how to do it properly other than to say that there were four tabs locking into place on my Super Mario Bros. 3 Famicom cartridge: two at the top, and one on each side (see the picture for positions). Your best bet for dismantling a cart without breaking anything is to use a very flat, thin, but wide-bladed screwdriver to try to pry it open.
<br />
<br />Yeah, that's it. I was wondering how NES developers would go about this task. Yeah, so I'm not as unintelligent as you say I am. There's no reason to call people stupid. That's why koitsu left, remember?

		

